Truth: Key provisions of the Reorganization Act of 1977 (5 U.S.C. 901) still remain in effect: “The President shall from time to time examine the organization of all agencies and shall determine what changes in such organization are necessary to carry out any policy set forth” in this statute, including but not limited to: - “To reduce expenditures and promote economy to the fullest extent consistent with the efficient operation of the Government" - “To reduce the number of agencies by consolidating those having similar functions under a single head, and to abolish such agencies or functions thereof as may not be necessary for the efficient conduct of the Government.” The expired provisions of this statute are the ones that gave Congress the power to stop the President from acting—the expiry of which arguably strengthens the President’s ability to use executive power to drive these changes under limited circumstances specified in the statute.

text: It was a disastrous week for Joe Biden. VIETNAM: Biden began the week with a 30+ minute meltdown in Vietnam, where he took a handful of pre-written questions from pre-selected reporters in a “press conference” that more closely resembled the ramblings of a madman. Then, he announced he was “going to bed.” 9/11: He then returned to the United States, where he became the first president in 22 years to mark the anniversary of the 9/11 attacks not at an attack site. Instead, Biden delivered brief remarks during a refueling stop in Alaska, where he falsely claimed to have visited Ground Zero “the next day” — which didn’t happen. IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY: On Tuesday, Speaker Kevin McCarthy directed House committees to begin a formal impeachment inquiry into Biden over allegations of influence peddling, corruption, and abuse of power — and Americans largely support it. In fact, 59 percent of Americans are “concerned about whether Joe Biden committed wrongdoing related to his son Hunter Biden’s business dealings,” including 65 percent of independents. BIDENFLATION: On Wednesday, news broke that inflation surged to 3.7 percent year-over-year in August — “hotter than expected” and more than twice the rate it was when Biden took office — as the Biden administration continues its streak of being wrong on inflation every step of the way. INDICTMENT: Hunter Biden was indicted on felony gun charges, just weeks after a sweetheart plea deal from Biden’s DOJ fell apart under basic scrutiny from a federal judge — and more charges are likely coming. BIDENOMICS: On Thursday, Biden attempted to sell his failed “Bidenomics” agenda with a speech in Maryland. Instead, Biden filled the speech with outlandish promises, made-up stories, and casual racism. KAMALA: Everyone knows Kamala Harris is a liability — and this week, the dam apparently broke. Democrat Reps. Nancy Pelosi and Jamie Raskin didn’t hold back, refusing — repeatedly — to throw their unwavering support behind Harris. STRIKE: Biden, who fancies himself the “most pro-union president” in history, couldn’t stop the United Auto Workers from striking — even though he said it wouldn’t happen. “I don’t know what [Biden] has done,” said one local UAW president. With weeks like these, is anyone surprised 70 percent of Americans say things are going BADLY under Biden? No wonder he’s retreating to Delaware for the weekend — again.
